Species and Riparian,  A fairly extensive Italian thistle infestation is degrading the ripairan system in two areas, Flyaway Gulch and David Gulch.  Causal factor has not been determined and needs to be investigated further.
Species, several invasive species occur.  Causal factor is identified as a road, where vehicular traffic is transporting and spreading weed seed.
Species, Invasive species present.  Yellow starthistle, Italian thistle, oblong spurge, and Himalayan blackberry.  Livestock grazing does not apear to be a causal factor.
Species, Invasive species present.  Yellow starthistle, Italian thistle, oblong spurge, and Himalayan blackberry.  Livestock grazing does not apear to be a causal factor.

Species, several invasive species occur.  Livestock grazing is probably contributing to the spread of noxious weeds in riparian area.  Riparian, riparian areas are classified as functional at risk with a downward trend.  Cattle are trampling ripraian vegetation especially in Stone Corral area.

Riparian, a 1/4 mile riparian area was considered non-functional.  Riparian zone did not extend beyond the active channel.  Weedy non-native plants dominated the floodplain.  Woody riparian species were greatly impacted.  They are being heavily browsed by livestock, and are mostly eliminated.  In some areas there is no water in the streambed due to lack of riparian vegetation.

Species, invasive species, particularly Iberian starthistle is present in Ned Gulch riparian area.  Riparian, Ned Gulch was assessed as functional at risk with a downward trend.  Besides invasive weeds, there is considerable browsing on willows and other riparian vegetation from cattle grazing.
Soils, lack of ground cover due to overgrazing.  Grazing has not occurred on the allotment since a wild fire in 2000.  Ground cover has recovered since cattle have been removed from the allotment.

Soils, Water Quality, Plant and Animal Habitat, and Special Status Species Habitat were partially met:  The sheep are not a contributor to the non attainment of those standards.

Special Status Species Habitats partially met:  The Western Burrowing owl and the Sage Grouse standard not being met in the checkerboard area on the allotment.  The soil standard is not being met in the checkerboard area in the allotment or in some of the lower elevations that burned.
Plant and Animal Habitat partially met: Given the uncontrollable movement and variable numbers of wild horses, it is not possible to assure forage would be available for livestock.
